rComments: I REALLY didn't like his teaching style although he was a very kind professor. His explanations of concepts were really scattered and just really difficult to follow in class. Luckily, you really only need to worry about what he has written in the course notes. He provides everything you need in those pages. Follow those and you'll be good to go.

Dr. Figeys is a very intelligent man, and has a bit of an accent; his teaching methods are good however is sometimes hard to understand. His kinetics section has multiple equations and derivations, where most are tested on the final exams. My advice: memorize all the equations and understand them!!!

Accent is confusing. He is confusing. Teaches very basic stuff, although asks ridiculously advanced questions on exams. Passes through advanced concepts very quickly in class, although he asks if we understand. Very tricky on exams.
Amazing guy, with a great sense of humour. Would take his class again
Accent is sometimes hard to understand, and he moves fast. He knows his stuff though and is good at explaining.

Best out of Bennett and Mezl. His midterm and test questions weren't too bad if you memorize the formulas, ALL OF THEM. Wish he taught the whole class tbh cause the other two prof's questions were just not my cup of tea.

Dr. Figeys was boring but it was simply the nature of the material he was covering and he tried to make it interesting with metaphors and cooking recipes! His exam questions were  extremely easy and his marking scheme isn't anywhere near as strict as Mezl's or Bennett's. Advice for the kinetics part: memorize the formulas cuz it guarantees A+
Really bad lecturer and bad at explaining concepts...that being said he has the easiest exam questions by far! Memorize those amino acids early and don't get caught up in the details of his notes!
What a cutie! His accent isn't bad at all! Really nice guy, I'd recommend him. :)
Dr Figeys is a kind hearted man. Though his accent is relatively strong, his enthusiasm and knowledge helped with the clarity of his lectures. Fantastic teacher and wonderful man. :)

Not overtly difficult. Kinetics section is difficult but he expects you to know it inside and out. Evaluation questions weren't too hard. Somewhat monotonous and has a french accent, so enthusiasm isn't his strong point. Tries to use fun analogies/examples. You'll have to learn your 20 amino acid structures quickly.
Nice guy but very hard to understand. In fairness he rushed thru tested material and then made the final stupidly hard.  He's not that great and I'm not not impressed

Straight-forward lecture notes and lecturing style, although it can get dry when he's talking about kinetics and basic stuff. Luckily he tries to add some humor into it with some odd analogies. His questions on exams are very straight-forward, if you have him you'll appreciate his questions on the exam compared to the other profs.

Great prof with a great sense of humor. Evaluations are based on understanding rather than useless memorizing. Tells you what's important to know. Great prof! Avoid the French Section if you can and take biochem with him instead.
He's okay. He's really boring and talks nonsense a lot of the time. Nice guy, but I wish he would put more effort into making the material seem a bit more interesting.
At first I wasn't really too fond of him, but as lectures went on he started revealing his 'awesome side.' His sense of humor is pretty good
